April 2, 2015

Summary

  • Whole blood is a heterogeneous collection of different cell types
    • Lymphcytes, Monocytes, Granulocytes.
  • Each type has a very different DNAm profile
    • large between cell type differences
  • Cellular composition explains much of the observed variability in DNA methylation
    • need to be ajusted for if confounding with covariate of interest.
  • Cellular composition correlates strongly with global DNAm profiless
    • High correlation between DNAm variance and composition variance : PCA biplot
  • Jaffe et al.2014

Age related findings

  • Strong evidence of cell composition change across age in blood.
  • High levels confounding between age related variability and cellular composition at the CPG level
  • Cell type proportions changes with age following monotonic patterns
  • Confounding between cell composition and age leads to false positives

Algorithm

  • first designed for Illumina 27K Chip by Houseman et al. (2012)
    • identified 500 CpGs that discriminated cellular composition in flow-sorted cell populations
    • fites a nonlinear random effects model at each of these CpGs
    • estimate the coefficient for each cellular component
    • use these coeficeints to predict the relative proportions of each cellular components
  • modified by Jaffe et al (2014)
    • using linear modeling across 600 composition -discriminating probes.
    • implemented in R - minfi Bioconducto package
    • CD4+, CD8+, NK, B cells, Monocytes, Granulocytes
